  "prompt": "What is story behind the war between Lord Ram and Hanuman?",
  "response": "The story of the conflict between Lord Ram and Hanuman doesn\u2019t actually exist within traditional Hindu texts such as the Ramayana and Mahabharata. In these texts, Lord Ram and Hanuman share a deep bond of devotion and friendship, rather than enmity. \n\nHanuman is portrayed as an ardent devotee of Lord Ram in the Ramayana, and his loyalty, bravery, strength, and unwavering devotion to Ram are highlighted throughout the epic. Hanuman plays a pivotal role in the search for Sita, Ram\u2019s wife, who is abducted by Ravana, the demon king of Lanka. Hanuman's extraordinary feats, from leaping across the ocean to reaching Lanka and burning it in half after his tail was set afire, to his participation in the battle against Ravana, are celebrated.\n\nOne possible source of confusion might be the misinterpretation or creative variations found in some folk tales or newer writings, not considered canonical. In these cases, it might be due to storytelling liberties taken by authors or creators in an attempt to create dynamic narratives. However, these are not part of the traditional and widely accepted Hindu scriptures.\n\nIn the canonical texts, there is no war or conflict between Lord Ram and Hanuman; instead, their relationship is defined by mutual respect, devotion, and unwavering loyalty.",
